Who likes artifficial life, stone giants and jews? well I have something for you. Get it? You, jew. Badum tss.


The Golem by Jorge Luis Borges tells us the classis story of Prague's Golem, however, more than a simple cuirous storyId dare to say that it is a reflction on the nature of the creator and his or her take on the creation, and the always present imperfections in the act of creation. It naturally flawed and imperfect, observation that is confirmed by the final verse which, after the poem tells us how many flaws Leon Juda ( the rabbi who created the golem) finds in his creation, closes the composition with the phrase, "and the same thought God of his Rabbi in Prague". Besides that stone giant is badass.
